extends layout.pug

block content
  section.hero
    .hero-inner
      .hero-copy
        p.brand-lockup Arbiter
        h1.hero-title Your agent workspace, in the terminal.
        p.hero-lede Run parallel agent conversations, watch tools and diffs stream live, and return to saved work without leaving your shell.
        .install-callout(aria-label="Install command")
          span Install Arbiter
          code= installCommand
          button.button(
            type="button"
            data-copy-install=installCommand
          ) Copy
        .hero-actions
          a.text-link(href="#tui") See the TUI ↓
          a.text-link(href="/docs/getting-started/local/") Read local setup →
      p.hero-qualifier Prebuilt for macOS Apple silicon and Linux x86_64. Apache-2.0. Bring an OpenRouter key or configure Ollama.

  section#tui.product-stage
    .product-stage-inner
      .product-heading
        div
          h2 One terminal. Multiple agents in motion.
        p.product-lede Each pane is an independent conversation with its own agent, history, input queue, and live output. Split the workspace, keep typing while work streams, and stop one pane without interrupting the others.
      .product-frame
        img(
          src="/assets/terminal.jpg"
          alt="Arbiter TUI showing parallel conversations, streamed output, tool activity, and inline diff rendering"
          width="2250"
          height="1540"
        )
      .product-features
        article
          h3 Parallel panes
          p Run research, planning, review, and implementation conversations side by side.
        article
          h3 Visible work
          p Follow streamed responses, tool status, token usage, and code diffs as each turn runs.
        article
          h3 Conversation history
          p Return to saved threads and continue with the agent’s existing context.

  section#workflow.section
    .section-inner
      .workflow-grid
        .workflow-copy
          h2 Stay in control without babysitting every turn.
          p.section-lede Arbiter keeps the work visible while agents reason, delegate, and act.
        .steps
          .step
            span 01
            strong Ask
            p Start with plain language in the focused pane.
          .step
            span 02
            strong Split
            p Open another pane or let an agent delegate work to a specialist.
          .step
            span 03
            strong Inspect
            p Follow streamed output, tool summaries, diffs, and failures while work runs.
          .step
            span 04
            strong Continue
            p Reopen a saved conversation and pick up where you stopped.

  section#why.section.section-band
    .section-inner
      h2 Built as a terminal workspace, not a chat box.
      .spec-matrix
        article.spec-cell.spec-cell-signal
          h3 Agents you can inspect
          p Agent behavior, models, and allowed capabilities live in editable configuration—not behind a hosted UI.
          code definitions: ~/.arbiter/agents/*.json
        article.spec-cell
          h3 Actions gated by the runtime
          p Each agent has an explicit capability allowlist. Optional advisor gates can review a terminating result before it is returned.
          code capabilities: explicit allowlist
        article.spec-cell
          h3 Tools in the same stream
          p Agents fetch, write, delegate, schedule, use memory, and call configured integrations while their output streams.
          code protocol: writ / line-oriented
        article.spec-cell
          h3 Local first, network optional
          p Work in the TUI, invoke one agent from a script, or expose the runtime through HTTP and SSE.
          code surfaces: TUI / CLI / HTTP+SSE

  section#sessions.section
    .section-inner
      .sessions-copy
        h2 Find the command, conversation, or output you need.
        p.section-lede Use the conversation sidebar to move between threads, queue another message while an agent works, inspect live token and tool activity, and run background loops without flooding the foreground.
        p.section-note Choose from built-in themes or edit the JSON theme system to match your terminal.

  section#interfaces.section.section-band
    .section-inner
      .interfaces-heading
        div
          h2 Automate the same runtime when you are ready.
        p.section-lede One orchestration loop, multiple ports. Start in the terminal; connect scripts, clients, and remote tools when the workflow needs them.
      .port-list
        article
          strong Script
          p One-shot CLI invocations against the local runtime.
        article
          strong Client
          p HTTP and SSE for remote tools and custom clients.
        article
          strong Integrations
          p MCP and A2A bridges into the same agent loop.

  section#trust.section.trust-section
    .section-inner
      h2 Local control, with explicit boundaries.
      .trust-grid
        article
          p Arbiter stores configuration and local state under #[code ~/.arbiter/]. Model requests go to the provider you configure.
        article
          p Interactive shell execution can access anything available to your user account. Start with #[code arbiter --no-exec] when you do not want agents to run shell commands.
        article
          p Arbiter is experimental pre-1.0 software. Interfaces and configuration may change between releases.
      .link-row
        a.text-link(href="https://github.com/tylerreckart/arbiter/blob/main/SECURITY.md") Read the security model →
        a.text-link(href=philosophyHref) Read the philosophy →

  section#install.install-section
    .section-inner
      .install-copy
        h2 From download to the TUI in three commands.
        p.section-lede Prebuilt for macOS Apple silicon and Linux x86_64. Other platforms can build from source.
      .direct-download
        a.mac-download-button(href=macDownloadUrl)
          span.download-glyph(aria-hidden="true") ↓
          span
            strong Download for macOS
            small Apple silicon · #{binaryRelease} · tar.gz
      .install-console
        .install-steps
          .install-step
            span 01
            code= installCommand
            button.button(
              type="button"
              data-copy-install=installCommand
            ) Copy
          .install-step
            span 02
            code arbiter --init
            small Create editable starter agent definitions.
          .install-step
            span 03
            code arbiter
            small Launch the terminal workspace.
      .first-prompt
        p “Help me turn this project into a concrete plan. Ask what you need to know, then delegate research and review to separate agents.”
      .link-row
        a.text-link(href=gettingStartedHref) Read local setup →
        a.text-link(href="https://github.com/tylerreckart/arbiter/blob/web/web/install.sh") Review the installer →
        a.text-link(href="/docs/getting-started/local/#install-the-binary") Build from source →
